commit abeff54785ba8f72169986b2fc24d83b0b1903f9
Author: Anton Dvornikov <prilive.company@gmail.com>
Date:   Fri May 8 12:21:10 2026 +0000

    feature/second-opinion: v1.6.0 anchoring-resistant review (Pass A + matrix + research packet)
    
    Implements docs/specs/second-opinion-v1.6.0-spec.md. Three new Tier-1
    artifacts close the anchoring failure mode in cross-model review;
    three opt-in flags + one killswitch make rollout safe; existing v1.5.x
    flow unchanged when flags are off.
    
    DESIGN SUMMARY (full rationale in spec):
    
    Anchoring problem: in v1.5.x, Codex sees Claude's plan as input to its
    review. Codex's response is anchored on Claude's framing. The literature
    (2025–2026) on multi-agent review converges: independent generation
    captures different blind spots; review-after-exposure-to-framing erodes
    them. This is upstream of the iterative-debate sycophancy problem
    (which v1.5.x correctly closed via single-pass).
    
    v1.6.0 adds:
      Pass A — Codex generates its OWN design BEFORE seeing Claude's plan;
        that design becomes the anchor for the comparison review (Pass B).
        NOT a debate round; structurally ensemble-style, not back-and-forth.
      Concern Disposition Matrix — replaces v1.5.x free-form rebuttal text;
        every Codex finding gets a row with mandatory Disposition. Hook
        validates row count == finding count.
      Research packet — anchors Codex's review against the same evidence
        Claude consulted; ≥3 authoritative sources required for Tier 1.
      Codebase grep invitation — Pass B prompt explicitly invites Codex to
        use its read-only access to grep the codebase for cross-file
        consistency. Closes the parasitoid integration-bug class.
      Closure check — diff-review prompt includes the prior plan-review
        matrix, with instruction to verify each ACCEPTED finding was
        actually implemented.
      Patterns pre-pass — adjudication template gains a cross-cutting
        observations section before per-finding rows.
    
    ROLLOUT SAFETY:
    
    All three Tier-1 artifact REQUIREMENTS are opt-in flags in
    .tdd/tdd-config.json (default false):
      second_opinion.require_research_packet_tier1
      second_opinion.require_pass_a_tier1
      second_opinion.require_disposition_matrix_tier1
    
    Pass A itself runs whenever Tier 1 + plan + research packet present, but
    the require_pass_a_tier1 flag controls whether the artifact is required
    to land Tier 1 edits. Killswitch SECOND_OPINION_PASS_A_DISABLE=1 turns
    Pass A off entirely (skill skips Pass A; hook skips its check).
    
    Operators flip flags in any order based on their eval-harness results.
    Recommended order:
      1. Matrix flag first (lowest cost, immediate discipline gain)
      2. Packet flag next (one-time spec-phase habit)
      3. Pass A flag last (highest value if eval shows it works)
    
    WHAT CHANGED:
    
    NEW FILES:
      .tdd/templates/research-packet-template.md
      .tdd/templates/independent-design-template.md
      .tdd/templates/disposition-matrix-template.md
      scripts/migrate-rebuttal-to-matrix.sh
      docs/specs/second-opinion-v1.6.0-spec.md   (already added separately)
    
    EDITED:
      .claude/skills/second-opinion/SKILL.md
        - Pass A logic (Tier-1 gated, with killswitch and research-packet
          precondition; falls back gracefully if Codex returns nothing)
        - Codebase grep invitation in Pass B prompt
        - Closure check block (diff-review with prior matrix in prompt)
        - Step 6 split into 6a (existing adjudication) + 6b (matrix template
          + discipline rules)
        - round1.json save (best-effort; required for matrix row-count check)
    
      .claude/hooks/require-second-opinion.sh
        - Three flag-gated Tier-1 artifact checks: research packet (≥3
          sources), Pass A artifact (mtime <60min, with killswitch),
          disposition matrix (row count == round1.json findings count)
        - Default-off behavior preserved: existing tests pass without
          changes
    
      .tdd/tdd-config.json
        - second_opinion.require_research_packet_tier1: false
        - second_opinion.require_pass_a_tier1: false
        - second_opinion.require_disposition_matrix_tier1: false
    
      .claude/rules/go-tdd.md
        - New "v1.6.0 — anchoring-resistant review" section
        - Documents three artifacts, why three flags not one, recommended
          flip order, link to full spec
    
      scripts/tdd-test-hooks.sh
        - 13 new smoke tests (default-off allows; each flag tested for
          deny + allow paths; killswitch; non-Tier-1 isolation; migration
          script + idempotency)
    
    SMOKE TESTS: 68 → 81 (+13 new):
      - v1.6.0 flags default off: Tier 1 edit allowed without new artifacts
      - require_research_packet_tier1=true + missing packet → deny
      - research-packet with 2 sources (<3) → deny
      - research-packet with 3 sources → allow
      - require_pass_a_tier1=true + missing independent-design → deny
      - fresh independent-design → allow
      - SECOND_OPINION_PASS_A_DISABLE=1 bypasses Pass A check
      - require_disposition_matrix_tier1=true + missing matrix → deny
      - matrix rows ≠ round1.json findings → deny (with awk-based row count)
      - matrix rows == round1.json findings → allow
      - non-Tier-1 edit unaffected by v1.6.0 flags
      - migrate-rebuttal-to-matrix.sh produces matrix with discipline markers
      - migrate-rebuttal-to-matrix.sh is idempotent
    
    WHAT IS NOT IN THIS COMMIT (per spec rejections):
    
      - No Round 3 / counter-review. Literature unambiguous; v1.5.x's
        single-pass-by-design line stays.
      - No 8-state machine. v1.5.2's 4-marker model is unchanged.
      - No 4th marker (e.g., "Deep review reconciled: yes"). The matrix's
        existence + row-count check IS the gate.
      - No 3-tier classifier. Tier 1 path classification carries the load.
      - No role-theater subagents. Same Claude with phase-specific prompts.
      - No new hooks. Existing 8 hooks cover all gates.
      - No general internet research integration. Only codebase grep is
        added (which Codex already has via read-only sandbox).
      - No comprehensive-spec generation. The plan IS the spec.
    
    VALIDATION GATE (per spec §8):
    
    Pass A is the only adoption whose codebase-specific value is unproven.
    The other five (matrix, packet, codebase grep, closure check, patterns
    pre-pass) are independently motivated. Recommended trial period: two
    weeks under the killswitch + flag, with eval against v1.5.2 baseline
    on the 30-fixture set. If Pass A doesn't catch ≥1 additional real
    defect per 10 fixtures with ≤1 false positive per 10, drop Pass A and
    keep the other five (which ship safely regardless).
    
    CITATIONS DISCLAIMER:
    
    The spec rests on directional claims from the 2025–2026 literature
    (anchoring bias in AI peer review, ensembling > debate, confirmation
    bias in LLM code review, sparsification). The specific paper citations
    in the consultant's analysis (arXiv 2603.18740 / 2406.12708 / Choi et
    al. Aug 2025 / NAACL 2025) are plausible but unverified by me
    (knowledge cutoff: January 2026). The directions are consistent with
    what I know; the design rests on directions, not paper-by-paper.

commit 111e64a0ccd11f3a5cf2c32e189f5ccd40b1a0ef
Author: Anton Dvornikov <prilive.company@gmail.com>
Date:   Fri May 8 11:44:27 2026 +0000

    feature/second-opinion: pin /second-opinion to most-powerful Codex model by default
    
    Per user preference (memorized: "Always use the most powerful, latest
    model — never downgrade for cost/latency"), flip the non-Tier-1 default
    from gpt-5.4-mini to gpt-5.5 so review quality dominates over cost on
    every cycle.
    
    Old behavior:
      Tier 1     → gpt-5.5
      non-Tier-1 → gpt-5.4-mini  (cost/latency optimization)
    
    New behavior:
      Tier 1     → gpt-5.5
      non-Tier-1 → gpt-5.5
    
    Two layers of override (config-first project knob; env var per-invocation):
    
      .tdd/tdd-config.json (NEW second_opinion block):
        {
          "second_opinion": {
            "model_tier1": "gpt-5.5",
            "model_default": "gpt-5.5",
            "fallback_model": "gpt-5.4"
          }
        }
    
      Resolution order (highest first):
        1. Env var (SECOND_OPINION_MODEL_TIER1 / _DEFAULT / _FALLBACK)
        2. Legacy single-knob env var SECOND_OPINION_MODEL (sets both)
        3. Config field .tdd/tdd-config.json second_opinion.{...}
        4. Hardcoded fallback in SKILL.md (gpt-5.5 / gpt-5.5 / gpt-5.4)
    
    Projects that prefer the older cost-optimized behavior can set
    model_default to gpt-5.4-mini in their tdd-config.json. Env vars still
    override per-invocation.
    
    Note on auth: gpt-5.5 needs ChatGPT-account auth via `codex login`.
    With API-key auth (CODEX_API_KEY / OPENAI_API_KEY), the skill's
    existing run_codex helper falls back to fallback_model (gpt-5.4)
    automatically. doctor.sh already warns on this auth-mode/model
    mismatch — no change needed there.
    
    Note on model name: gpt-5.5 is the most powerful Codex model the
    repo references. If a newer Codex model has shipped since this
    commit, projects can update via the new config field without
    patching SKILL.md.
    
    WHAT CHANGED:
      .tdd/tdd-config.json
        + second_opinion block with model defaults + doc comment
    
      .claude/skills/second-opinion/SKILL.md
        - Replaced "tier-aware to keep cost reasonable" framing with
          "default to most powerful; opt-down via config if you want"
        - Added config-read step before env-var resolution
        - Hardcoded fallback for default tier: gpt-5.4-mini → gpt-5.5
        - Override knobs section now documents both env vars AND config
    
    Smoke tests: 68 still passing (config block reads cleanly; existing
    behavior unchanged for projects that don't set the field).

commit dc9835e041f44e17eba9c433eeaa389a8dba32fb
Author: Anton Dvornikov <prilive.company@gmail.com>
Date:   Fri May 8 11:17:39 2026 +0000

    feature/second-opinion: integration guards (parasitoid trial feedback)
    
    Parasitoid 7-day trial caught 9 design bugs via /second-opinion plan
    review (5 P1 + 4 P2) — working as designed. But 3 P0/P1 integration
    bugs slipped through:
    
      - trend_strategy.go writes metadata["orderLinkId"] (camelCase);
        new G4 executeSignal reads metadata["order_link_id"] (snake_case).
        Every trend signal silently fails after G4 ships.
      - grid_calculator.go emits OrderLinkId: "" for spot grid; the
        GenerateGridOrderLinkId helper exists but is only called for bear
        grid. Every spot-grid signal silently fails.
      - strategy_orchestrator.go::sellProfitablePositions calls
        ExchangeService.PlaceOrder directly during grid->trend transitions,
        bypassing G4 entirely.
    
    The pattern: plan review verifies the plan's internal consistency; it
    does not audit how the planned change interacts with the rest of the
    codebase. Structural property of plan-review-as-methodology, not a
    defect in the /second-opinion skill.
    
    Honest synthesis (vs the consultant's wire-audit proposal):
    
    ADOPTED:
      - lightweight grep-guards approach (deferred the auto-detect skill)
      - allowed_globs allowlist with ** for cross-directory
      - severity: deny | warn (warn for in-progress refactors)
      - rationale field linking each guard to a real bug
    
    REJECTED FROM CONSULTANT:
      - putting guards in the plan file. The planner's blind spot IS the
        guard-author's blind spot — if the planner could see the
        integration assumption, they'd plan correctly. Project-level
        guards accumulate institutional memory across cycles.
      - separate pre-green-commit.sh hook. Composed into the existing
        gate-tier1-commit.sh — one commit gate, all the checks.
      - file-list allowed_files. Used glob patterns instead so adding a
        new sanctioned file under internal/intent/v2/ doesn't require
        editing the allowlist.
      - the auto-detecting wire-audit skill. Auto-detection of integration
        boundaries is a research project; out of scope for a starter pack.
    
    DOCUMENTED HONESTLY:
      - guards are FALLBACK protection. Integration tests are primary.
        Decision tree in go-integration-guards.md: test first, type
        safety second, guard third.
      - allowed_globs grow over time. That's intentional — each addition
        forces a deliberate decision.
      - the starter pack ships the mechanism (hook + schema + decision
        tree). The actual project-specific guards live in each project's
        .tdd/tdd-config.json.
    
    WHAT CHANGED:
    
      .tdd/tdd-config.json
        + integration_guards: []  (default empty array)
        + schema doc inline as _integration_guards_schema
    
      .claude/hooks/gate-tier1-commit.sh
        + glob_to_regex helper handling **/, **, * with correct semantics
          (** matches zero+ segments per gitignore convention; * matches
          one segment)
        + guard scanner: jq-driven loop, grep -rlE per pattern, allowlist
          check, deny/warn collection
        + composed AFTER existing M4/green-proof/adjudication checks so
          one hook owns all commit-time gating
        + audit log entries for both deny and warn
    
      .claude/rules/go-integration-guards.md (NEW)
        + decision tree (test vs type safety vs guard)
        + schema reference
        + guard maintenance discipline (rationale-linked-to-bug)
        + friction note (allowed_globs need updates when sanctioned files
          grow — intentional)
    
      docs/process/tdd_workflow.md
        + brief "Integration guards (commit-time)" section pointing at the
          rule file
    
      scripts/tdd-test-hooks.sh
        + 7 new tests covering the full guard flow
    
    BUGS HIT DURING IMPLEMENTATION (caught + fixed in this commit):
    
      1. grep -rlE -- "$pattern" --include='*.go' was failing because the
         -- end-of-options separator before --include made GNU grep treat
         --include=*.go as a positional path arg. Caught by smoke test
         "no-match guard should pass" returning 1 violation in
         .tdd/tdd-config.json (where the pattern was stored). Fixed by
         putting -- AFTER all --include / --exclude-dir flags.
    
      2. glob_to_regex translated "internal/intent/**/*.go" to
         "^internal/intent/.*/[^/]*\\.go$", which required at least one
         intermediate path segment — meaning it matched
         "internal/intent/v2/tracker.go" but NOT
         "internal/intent/tracker.go". Fixed by translating "**/" as a
         distinct token "(.*/)?" (zero-or-more "segment/" prefixes,
         gitignore convention) before handling lone ** and *.
    
      3. The } character escape "${g//\}/\\}}" produced a stray }
         in the regex output ("^internal/intent/(.*/)?[^/]*\\.go}$") —
         bash's ${var//pat/repl} grammar mishandles literal } in
         replacements (the closing } of the substitution swallows it).
         Fixed by removing the { } escapes entirely — they aren't POSIX
         ERE specials in this context anyway. The smoke test
         "All-allowed should pass" caught this.
    
    SMOKE TESTS: 61 → 68 (+7 new):
      - Guard violation outside allowed_globs denies commit
      - Guard with all violators in allowed_globs allows commit
      - warn-severity guard logs warning but allows commit
      - empty integration_guards array allows commit (no-op)
      - guard with no matches allows commit
      - ** glob respects nested matches but still flags non-allowlisted
      - Multiple guards: deny + warn both reported, deny wins
    
    WHAT IS NOT IN THIS COMMIT (rejected or deferred):
    
      - Plan-level integration_guards section in current-plan.md.
        Deferred. Project-level handles 80% per the analysis.
        Future direction: extract from <!-- INTEGRATION_GUARDS_START -->
        markers in current-plan.md.
      - Auto-detecting wire-audit skill. Rejected as research project.
      - go-stringly-typed.md rule advocating typed metadata constants.
        Considered but kept this PR scoped to the hook + config + docs
        for one focused change. Worth a follow-up if the warn-severity
        guard for stringly-typed metadata sees real use.

commit cc425d3090fa991929a61f9bf368a646524fd806
Author: Anton Dvornikov <prilive.company@gmail.com>
Date:   Wed May 6 09:28:09 2026 +0000

    fix(ci): quote agents-md-sync script line so YAML parses it as a string
    
    GitLab CI rejected the pipeline with:
      jobs:agents-md-sync:script config should be a string or a nested
      array of strings up to 10 levels deep
    
    Root cause: the unquoted script item contained "Run: cp ..." inside
    the inline echo. YAML's flow rules treat the literal `: ` (colon-space)
    as a key-value separator even though it's inside a shell double-quoted
    string — the OUTER YAML scalar has no quotes, so YAML doesn't know about
    the shell quoting.
    
    YAML was parsing the script as:
      [{key: 'diff ... Run', value: 'cp ...; exit 1; }'}]
    i.e. a list-of-dicts instead of a list-of-strings, which GitLab rejects.
    
    Fix: wrap the whole script item in single quotes. YAML treats it as a
    plain string scalar.
    
    Pre-existing bug introduced in ae74fe9 (v1.1.0). Surfaced now because
    this is the first MR pipeline that ran the verify stage on a
    GitLab instance with the stricter parser.
    
    Verified with python3 -c yaml.safe_load: script[0] is now str.
    Scanned all other jobs: no similar issues.

commit 50e081a5eaac540b9b6523aa10042d9d53833547
Author: Anton Dvornikov <prilive.company@gmail.com>
Date:   Wed May 6 09:12:15 2026 +0000

    feature/second-opinion: TDD gate redesign — 4-marker model + commit hook + phase-aware tests
    
    Real-trial deadlock on pre-oauth-hardening-04052026 cycle: docs said
    3-phase workflow with 3 operator approvals; hook implemented 2-phase
    workflow with 1 operator approval. The third marker ("Human approved
    implementation") sounded like post-impl review but was used as
    pre-green authorization. Operator hit the boundary, paused; the cycle
    deadlocked.
    
    This commit synthesizes the developer's analysis + 2 consultant reviews
    (strong-4-marker vs minimal-rename) + my own analysis. Adopted the
    4-marker design (Consultant A) but with Consultant B's migration
    cleanliness; rejected the pre/post-green second-opinion split (B); rejected
    the layered 3-PR rollout (my earlier spec) for one coherent change.
    
    Honest synthesis (see docs/specs/tdd-gate-conflict-resolution-spec.md
    for the full reasoning):
    
    A's "audit semantic precision matters" argument is correct for governance-
    heavy code. Setting a marker named "Human approved implementation" before
    the implementation exists is a misleading audit claim. Worth the rename.
    
    A's "/second-opinion diff isn't a substitute for a third operator gate" is
    correct. A second AI catches code-shape errors a human eyeball misses, but
    a human gate-3 catches scope creep and "is this the right thing to ship"
    judgment. They are complementary, not equivalent. Adding the commit-time
    gate captures the protection the docs were reaching for.
    
    A's pre/post-green second-opinion split is over-engineering. Two
    artifacts means two staleness windows and two ways to drift. Single
    artifact + freshness check stays.
    
    B's migration cleanliness is right. Old marker name aliased for one
    minor version with stderr deprecation; sed-based migration script;
    smoke test for the alias path. Existing in-flight plans don't break.
    
    WHAT CHANGED:
    
      Four markers (was three):
        M1 Human approved spec       (gate 1, set after APPROVED SPEC)
