commit 60fc4b121d2c8319dafaa8d7cb8fc1eabbdf23f5
Author: Anton Dvornikov <prilive.company@gmail.com>
Date:   Sun May 3 11:37:42 2026 +0000

    feature/second-opinion: trial-feedback hardening (3 fixes from D2 trial run)
    
    Fixes from real-trial feedback on chore/trial-second-opinion (D2 run with
    cmd/status fixes + first real /second-opinion invocation). Synthesizes
    the developer report + two consultant reviews + my own analysis.
    
    PR1 — redact-patterns loader hardening
      Bug: comment lines in .claude/redact-patterns.txt were being parsed
      as regex. A comment like "# Universal patterns (cloud keys...)" with
      an unbalanced "(" silently emptied the entire diff on bsd-awk (macOS
      default). Codex was then invoked with an empty TARGET, returned "no
      diff content provided", and the audit log recorded a "successful"
      review with zero findings. Two failures in one: token waste + audit
      corruption.
    
      Fix: new load_redact_patterns() function in SKILL.md pre-filters
      the user file (drops comments + blank lines) AND validates each
      surviving regex with grep -E. Invalid patterns are logged to
      DEBUG_LOG and skipped — never block the hook. Awk loader keeps
      the same comment/blank skip as belt-and-suspenders.
    
      Adopted: Consultant B's package (warn+skip+audit, not Consultant
      A's fail-hard, which violates the never-blocks contract).
    
    PR2 — pre-Codex packet validation
      Defense-in-depth for the same silent-emptying class. Two checks
      between redaction and Codex invocation:
        1. 50-byte minimum on redacted output (a real plan/diff has at
           least a header).
        2. Ratio check: input >100B should retain >10% post-redaction.
           Below that, an over-broad pattern is probably eating
           everything.
      Either check failing skips the review (exit 0) and writes a
      diagnostic to stderr pointing at DEBUG_LOG.
    
      Adopted: Consultant B's two-check version. Rejected Consultant A's
      6-check version (TARGET-section regex, stderr-empty check, etc.) as
      over-engineered — the ratio check catches the same failure modes
      more cheaply.
    
    PR3 — PARTIAL discipline marker
      Most-valuable of the three. Real in-trial example: developer
      observed Claude labeling F2 as PARTIAL while functionally accepting
      100% of the finding — sycophancy theatre that the existing
      "Why this is correct:" marker doesn't catch (that marker only
      fires on P0+ACCEPT).
    
      Fix in three layers:
        1. SKILL.md Step 4: PARTIAL stance at any severity must include
           three sub-sections: 'What I am accepting:', 'What I am
           rejecting:', 'Why this split is correct:'. Names both failure
           modes (sycophancy theatre, deference theatre) so Claude has
           the vocabulary to recognize the trap.
        2. SKILL.md Step 6: adjudication artifact template gains a
           'findings:' list with per-finding stance + (for PARTIAL)
           accepted/rejected/why_split fields.
        3. require-second-opinion.sh: awk scan of the artifact denies
           any PARTIAL with empty/insubstantive 'rejected:' field
           (anti-patterns: blank/nothing/n/a/none/-/<10 chars).
    
      Adopted: Consultant B's three-section structure + anti-pattern
      rejection + sycophancy/deference-theatre framing. Rejected
      Consultant A's 5-field structure (Plan-code delta + Test impact
      duplicate fields elsewhere in the adjudication).
    
    Smoke tests: 35 → 43 passing (+8 new):
      - PARTIAL with empty 'rejected:' denied
      - PARTIAL with 'rejected: nothing' anti-pattern denied
      - PARTIAL with substantive 'rejected:' passes
      - ACCEPT stance (no PARTIAL markers needed) passes
      - Mixed ACCEPT + valid PARTIAL passes
      - load_redact_patterns keeps valid patterns from mixed file
      - load_redact_patterns handles comment-only file (no crash)
      - load_redact_patterns logs invalid regex to DEBUG_LOG
    
    The load_redact_patterns tests work by extracting the function
    from SKILL.md at test time (awk between 'load_redact_patterns()'
    and the matching closing brace). Brittle to future refactors
    of SKILL.md but catches the regression that matters most:
    silent comment-as-regex bypass.

commit c20fd43641186f7f4e75b8bb65994aec6b9bfc55
Author: Anton Dvornikov <prilive.company@gmail.com>
Date:   Sat May 2 09:24:31 2026 +0000

    feature/second-opinion: mandatory enforcement via 2 PreToolUse hooks (synthesis of 3 reviews)
    
    Real-world bypass: Claude judged a non-trivial cmd/status/main.go change
    as 'obvious cleanup' and skipped the second-opinion skill. Skill auto-
    invocation is description-driven; Claude's judgment was wrong; trial
    period surfaced this within 2 days. The user wants ALL non-trivial code
    changes to go through the second-opinion + TDD flow, mechanically.
    
    Synthesizes the developer report + two consultant proposals + my own
    analysis. Adopts the architectural agreement (PreToolUse hook, defense
    in depth) and the cheap mechanical fixes (mutating Bash blocking,
    pipefail guard); rejects the framework-level overengineering (8
    lifecycle scripts, .devflow/ dir, policy.json, current.json state
    machine, expires_at, 4-tier model, per-component waivers).
    
    NEW HOOK: .claude/hooks/require-second-opinion.sh
      Matches Edit|Write|MultiEdit|Bash. Mechanically denies code-changing
      tool calls until .tdd/second-opinion-completed.md exists with mtime
      within the last 60 minutes. The skill writes that file at the end
      of its workflow (Step 6 of SKILL.md, also added in this commit).
    
      For Tier 1 paths (per existing .tdd/tdd-config.json regexes), the
      hook ALSO requires .tdd/current-plan.md with all 3 APPROVED markers
      (additive to the existing require-tdd-state.sh).
    
      For trivial changes (.md, .txt, CHANGELOG*, README*, LICENSE*,
      .editorconfig, .gitignore, go.sum, .github/*, .gitlab-ci.yml, files
      under .tdd/.claude/.second-opinion/), the hook passes through.
      Skip list mirrors the skill's so the same trivial cases that the
      skill auto-skips also bypass the hook.
    
      For mutating Bash (sed -i, perl -i, gofmt -w, goimports -w,
      go mod tidy/edit/init, go get, go install, cat > file, tee,
      truncate, '>> file.go|sh|py|ts|js|json|yml|yaml|toml'), the hook
      also denies. Without this, Claude could bypass Edit/Write/MultiEdit
      entirely by writing files via Bash.
    
      Defense in depth (per known PreToolUse bugs anthropics/claude-code
      #37210, #18312, #41151, #21988, #4669, #24327): when denying, the
      hook applies four redundant layers:
        1. chmod 444 the target (restored after 8s) — works around #37210
           (Edit deny silently ignored on macOS)
        2. JSON 'permissionDecision: "deny"' — primary mechanism
        3. stderr <claude-directive> markup — works around #24327
           (Opus 4.6+ stop-instead-of-act on hook block)
        4. Exit code 2 — works around #41151 / #21988
    
      Killswitch: SECOND_OPINION_DISABLE=1 (env var only; no file marker
      bypass — env var is harder to forget about than a file).
    
    NEW HOOK: .claude/hooks/guard-bash-pipefail.sh
      Matches Bash. Catches the silent-failure pattern from the real
      failure mode you saw:
        go build ./... 2>&1 | head -10 && echo "exit: $?"  →  reports
        exit 0 despite the build failing, because head -10 returned 0.
      Without 'set -o pipefail', the upstream Go-tool exit code is masked
      by the downstream command. The hook denies any go/gofmt/goimports/
      golangci-lint/staticcheck/govulncheck/deadcode/unparam command that
      pipes through another tool without pipefail.
    
    UPDATED SKILL: .claude/skills/second-opinion/SKILL.md
      Added Step 6: 'Write the adjudication artifact (REQUIRED)'.
      Tells Claude to write .tdd/second-opinion-completed.md after Step 5
      (decide/surface). Without this file, the next code-changing tool
      call is denied.
    
    UPDATED settings.json:
      - Both new hooks registered on appropriate matchers.
      - Bash NOT added to permissions.allow (avoids #18312 shadow).
    
    UPDATED .gitignore:
      - .tdd/second-opinion-completed.md (per-cycle artifact)
      - .tdd/second-opinion-enforcement.log (audit log; paths only)
    
    UPDATED MAINTAINING.md: 'Mandatory enforcement of /second-opinion'
    section. Documents what was adopted from the consultants and what
    was rejected:
      - Adopted: PreToolUse architecture, defense-in-depth, mutating Bash
        blocking, pipefail guard.
      - Rejected: .devflow/ framework, policy.json, current.json state
        machine with 5 statuses, expires_at, 8 lifecycle scripts,
        per-component waivers, 4-tier model, project-specific Tier 1
        patterns in upstream.
    
    Smoke tests: 26/26 -> 35/35 (+9 new tests):
      - Edit on cmd/status/main.go without adjudication denied (the
        exact failure mode that triggered this work)
      - Bash 'cat > file.go' without adjudication denied
      - Read-only Bash 'git status' passes through
      - Edit on README.md passes through (always-allow path)
      - Edit allowed once adjudication artifact exists
      - SECOND_OPINION_DISABLE=1 killswitch bypasses the hook
      - go build | head without pipefail denied
      - set -o pipefail; go build | head allowed
      - go build alone (no pipe) passes

