    feature/second-opinion: broaden scope to any non-trivial change (v1.2.0 of skill)
    
    Per developer feedback + 2026 industry research (CodeRabbit/Greptile/Qodo
    all auto-fire on every PR, severity-filter downstream): the skill now
    auto-invokes for ANY non-trivial code change, not just Tier 1.
    
    Frontmatter (broaden + version bump 1.1.0 -> 1.2.0):
      - description rewritten from 'Tier 1-centric' to 'any non-trivial
        code change (Tier 1 or not)'.
      - when_to_use auto-invoke list expanded: any new feature, any bug
        with uncertain root cause, any cross-package change, any
        architecture / API decision, refactor >30 lines, any Tier 1 path.
      - when_to_use skip list explicit: typo, formatting, doc-only,
        single-line obvious bugfix, non-code project files, mid-Tier-1
        implementation already APPROVED, SECOND_OPINION_DISABLE=1, codex
        not installed.
    
    Bash body — four mechanical guards keep the broader scope sensible:
    
      1. skip_globs (NEW): files matching docs/lockfile/CI patterns are
         filtered out before counting lines. If nothing remains, skip the
         review entirely. Default skip set: *.md, *.txt, CHANGELOG*,
         README*, LICENSE*, .editorconfig, .gitignore, go.sum, .github/*,
         .gitlab-ci.yml.
    
      2. min_substantive_lines: 5 (NEW): drops whitespace-only and pure
         comment +/- lines from the count. A 50-line gofmt diff reads as 0
         substantive lines and skips. A 6-line bug fix reviews.
    
      3. Lower upper bound from 4000 -> 2000 lines (per 2026 AI-review
         benchmarks; quality drops above ~1000-2000 lines).
    
      4. Lower bound: 10 lines (unchanged).
    
    Tier-aware model selection (NEW):
      - SECOND_OPINION_MODEL_TIER1   = gpt-5.5         (default; ChatGPT auth only)
      - SECOND_OPINION_MODEL_DEFAULT = gpt-5.4-mini    (default; works with both)
      - SECOND_OPINION_MODEL          = legacy single knob (used for both if set)
      - SECOND_OPINION_FALLBACK_MODEL = gpt-5.4         (used if primary fails)
    
      Decision logic: read .tdd/tdd-config.json tier1_path_regexes; if any
      changed file matches, use tier1_model + 'Tier 1' label. Otherwise
      use default_model + 'non-Tier-1' label. Both shown in chat output.
    
      This converts the Tier 1 concept from yes/no gating into how-deep-
      should-the-review-be. Cheaper + faster on routine work, deeper on
      high-stakes.
    
    Chat output now shows scope and model:
      ## Second opinion (scope: <Tier label>, model: <model name>)
    
    MAINTAINING.md updated with rationale: tier-aware model section
    expanded; new 'mechanical filters' section explains the four guards;
    'why no rate budget' and 'why no policy.json' sections explain
    deliberate choices vs the consultant proposals we rejected.
    
    Synthesized from:
      - Consultant A (universal availability, tier-aware depth) — adopted
        the spirit, rejected the framework (8 scripts, policy.json, state
        machine, templates dir).
      - Consultant B (skip_globs, min_substantive_lines, tier-aware model
        via mechanical filter) — adopted the cheap mechanical guards,
        rejected the hook-architecture rate budget that doesn't apply to
        skill-based throttling.
      - My own analysis (lower upper bound to 2000 per 2026 research,
        test with realistic prompts).
    
    Rejected from both consultants:
